            , a sheet, nine shillings in the name of Holton, a napkin and a coffee-mill, in the name of Wier.</p>
               <p>WILLIAM FORRESTER. I am servant to Mr. Lane, Drury-lane. I have two tablecloths pawned on the 8th of January, for a guinea-and-a-half, in the name of Jane Holton, a tent-bed furniture, pawned on the same day by Wier, in the name of Holton, and a pair of boots, ten shillings, in the name of Wier.</p>
               <p>Holton said nothing in her defence.</p>
               <p>Wier's Defence. Mrs. Holton sent me with the different articles to pledge, she acted more as a mistress than a servent, I did as Holton ordered me, I always gave her the money.</p>
               <p>HOLTON, <rs id="t18100919-128-verdict735" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18100919-128-verdict735" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
